            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>“Oh, yes, that road down to Moab will be okay for your pickup camper.”<br /><br />
                
                Those were the words in response to a question if we could go down that side of the mountain from up above Moab when we were visiting Dead Horse Point in Utah. We were vacationing in southern Utah with my sister Ethel and her husband Wayne, who were driving a VW bus. Ken and I were a bit apprehensive about that road down off the mountain because of the size of our camper, but the ranger up there assured us that it would be okay, so we started down with a bit of fear and trepidation. 
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                    
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                As we approached the turn that would take us down another ranger coming along in a jeep, he asked us where we were going in our big outfit. He then warned us that the trail was hairpin sharp, and that there was no turning back once we started—but we had already started down, so we couldn’t turn back! After a bit of consulting with Ethel, we decided to go for it and continue on. The ranger shook his head and said, “Good luck.” 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Within the first five minutes, we knew we had made a not so good choice. The road was so narrow and steep down that side of the mountain that we had to back up and turn several times just to get around each hairpin turn! Our pickup was long and the camper heavy so it caused us much fear at each turn: “Oh…oh…can we make this one?” I got out of the pickup to guide Ken at each of the turns, and after much backing and adjusting the angle of the pickup, we managed to get another hairpin behind us! <br /><br />

                    I watched for Ethel and Wayne to come along behind us, but they had no problem negotiating turns in the road because of the compact VW they were in. I asked her if they were okay and she said, “Well you are a lot bigger than we are so if you make the turn then we know we can!” As we looked over the side of the road down to the next curve, we found that because of the steepness of that side, we couldn't even see the road below us or the next turn! But we had no choice but to go on and just do it, with a prayer, much patience, and another prayer. “Don't look over the side again!” And on we went for about an hour. <br /><br />

                    Talk about counting blessings, when we finally leveled off on flat ground, we just sat in that pickup and wiped away a few tears. Moab was across the desert a few miles yet but we were on flat ground; these were blessings because we were counting them all! <br /><br />

                    When we arrived in Moab we pulled into a station for gas, and when the attendant asked where we were from, we told him. He said, astounded, “No way, no way could that pickup and camper make it down that JEEP TRAIL!”
 
                </span>

