                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    As it turned out, Ricks College and the homes up there became a haven for many hundreds of those whose homes were destroyed. My big concern was for the Public Health Office, a newly-built health department building that we had only been using for a few months. I had someone notify the sheriff the next day that I needed to get to my office to remove vaccine materials and other chemicals and any other record materials that could be salvaged. <br /><br />

                    The sheriff came to the bottom of the hill by Smith Park and took me in a row boat to the office and we were able to take out from there all that needed to be kept safe. The health department was soon established in the rock house next to the drive, which was high enough that only the basement apartment had water in it. <br /><br />

                    The apartment in the basement where Robert and Laurie lived was filled with flood water and all of their possessions were soaked and ruined. Marlon's apartment was also totally flooded and they lived in our camper parked in our backyard for awhile. The drive-in and the bottom apartments of the Norsemen were filled as well and so the work to get it cleaned up began. <br /><br />

                    The water in Rexburg eventually ran off and on down the valley. The 8th Ward chapel of which we were members only had a few inches of water and only had minor damage. A miracle there. Volunteers came from everywhere to help in the clean up of flooded Rexburg. Many faith-promoting incidents occurred during the next weeks and months following the tragedy of the Teton Dam breaking. Testimonies were strengthened and faith enlarged by those who were residents of Rexburg as well as those who came to help. <br /><br />

